direct_answer.text:
To find the maximum value of the expression $\frac{x - y}{x^4 + y^4 + 6}$, we need to complete the square in the denominator. Let's start by completing the square in the numerator so that it becomes a perfect square trinomial:

\begin{align*}
\frac{x - y}{(x^2)^2+(y^2)^2+\frac{6}{\left(\sqrt[4]{x^2}+\sqrt[4]{y^2}\right)^2}} & =\frac{\frac{x - y}{x^2}}{(x^2)^2+(y^2)^2+\frac{6}{\left(\sqrt[4]{x^2}+\sqrt[4]{y^2}\right)^2}} \\
& =\frac{u}{v},
\end{align*}

where
\begin{align*}
u & =\frac{x - y}{x^2} \\
v & =(x^2)^2+(y^2)^2+\frac{6}{\left(\sqrt[4]{x^2}+\sqrt[4]{y^2}\right)^2}
\end{align*}
